**Agent workflow:**  
Think \=\> Act \=\> Observe

**What is an Agent?**  
Let’s see the Agentic Workflow:

1) Agent receives a command  
2) Agent understands that command  
3) Before fulfilling the command, Agent engages in **reasoning & planning**, figuring out the **steps & tools** needed.  
4) Once planned, Agent starts to **act**  
5) To execute it’s plan, Agent uses **tools**  
6) Finally, Agent results the command

**Agent** \=\> AI model capable of reasoning, planning & interacting with the environment

Formal definition of an agent:  
*“An Agent is a system that leverages an AI model to interact with its environment in order to achieve a user-defined objective. It combines reasoning, planning, and the execution of actions (often via external tools) to fulfill tasks.”*

Agent comprises of **2 main parts**:

1) The Brain (AI model) \=\> handles **reasoning & planning**, decides **which action to take** based on the situation  
2) The Body (Capabilities & Tools) \=\> represents everything the **Agent is equipped to do**

**Note**: The scope of possible actions depends on what the agent has been equipped with  
Eg: Humans lack wings, thus they can’t perform the “fly” Action, but they can execute “walk”, “run”, “jump”, etc Actions as they are equipped with such tools and capabilities

**What type of AI model (The Brain) do we use for Agents?**  
LLMs (Large Language Models) \=\> most commonly found AI models  
LLMs takes input as **Text** and outputs **Text** as well  
Eg: GPT4 (OpenAI), LLama (Meta), Gemini (Google), etc

**Note**: Not just LLMs are the core AI models for Agents, if we want to understand the images as Inputs then LLMs are not work, go for **VLMs** (Vision Language Models)

But if you ask well-known chat applications like ChatGPT or HuggingChat to generate an image, they can\! How’s that possible?  
Solution: These LLMs uses **Tools** to create images, they use an Image Generation Tool

**What type of tasks can an Agent do?**  
An agent can perform any task we implement via **Tools** to complete **Actions**

Eg: I write an Agent to act as my personal assistant (like Siri / Alexa) on my computer, and I ask it to “send an email to my Manager asking for sick leave today” (**command**), I can give it some code to send emails (**Tool**), the Agent can use this Tool whenever it needs to send an email (**action**).

def send\_message\_to(recipient, message):  
    """Useful to send an e-mail message to a recipient"""  
    ...

LLMs will **generate the code to run the Tool** when it needs to, & thus fulfill the desired task

send\_message\_to("Manager", "Can I take sick leave today?")

The **design of the Tools** is very important & has a great impact on the quality of your Agent  
Some tasks might require specific Tools to be crafted, while others may be solved with general purpose tools like “web\_search”

**Note**: Actions are not the same as Tools. An action can involve the use of **multiple Tools** to complete.

Allowing an agent to interact with its environment **allows real-life usage for companies & individuals**  
Eg:

1) Personal Virtual Assistants  
2) Customer Service Chatbots  
3) AI Non-Playable Characters in a Video Game (NPCs)

**Summary of What is an Agent?**  
Agent is a system that uses AI model (LLM) as its core reasoning engine to:

1) Understand Natural Language \=\> to interpret & respond to instructions  
2) Reason & Plan \=\> make decisions & devise strategies to solve problems  
3) Interact with its environment \=\> gather info, take actions, observe the results of those actions

**What are LLMs?**  
An LLM is a type of AI model that excels at **understanding and generating human language**. Most LLMs nowadays are built on the **Transformers architecture** \- based on the **Attention** models (**Encoder-Decoder** Model).

There are **3 types of Transformers:**

1) Encoders	2\) Decoders	3\) Seq2Seq (Encoder-Decoder)

Although LLMs come in various forms, they are typically **Decoder-based** models with billions of parameters.  
![][image1]

**Encoders**  
Takes text (or other data) as Input and outputs a dense representation (or **embedding**) of that text  
Similar texts have **closer embeddings**  
Generates different vector representations for a word **based on the context** (Apple (fruit) vs Apple (company))  
Eg: BERT (Google)  
Applications: **Text Classification** (Sentiment Classification), **Semantic Search** (Keyword vs Semantic (Meanings) Search), **Named Entity Recognition** (to identify & classify key info in text)

**Decoders**  
Focuses on **generating new tokens** to complete a sequence, **one token at a time**  
Eg: **Llama** (Meta)  
Applications: Text generation, Chatbots, Code generation

**Seq2Seq (Encoder-Decoder)**  
Encoder first processes the input sequence into a context representation, then the decoder generates an output sequence  
Eg: T5 (Google), BART (Meta), GPT (OpenAI)  
Applications: Translation, Summarization, Paraphrasing (**Rewriting** in a different way while preserving **original meaning**)

**Note**: LLMs are often Decoder-based models  
Eg: Deepseek-R1 (DeepSeek), GPT4 (OpenAI), Llama3 (Meta), SmolLM2 (HuggingFace), Gemma (Google), Mistral (Mistral), etc

**Underlying principle of LLMs:**  
To predict the next token, given a sequence of previous tokens  
LLM might have a vocabulary of around 32,000 tokens (for Llama2)  
Each LLM has some **special tokens** specific to the model. LLMs use them to open & close the structured components of its generation.  
Most important special token is **End of sequence token** (EOS)  
Eg: GPT4 \<|endoftext|\>, Llama3 \<|eot\_id|\>, Deepseek \<|end\_of\_sentence|\>, SmolLM2 \<|im\_end|\>, Gemma \<end\_of\_turn\>

**Understanding Next token prediction:**  
LLMs are **AutoRegressive,** meaning that the **output from one pass** becomes the **input for the next** one.  
This loop continues till the model predicts the next token to be the EOS token, at which point the model can stop.

**What happens during a single decoding loop?**  
Once the input is **tokenized**, the model computes a representation of the sequence that captures the info about the **meaning & the position of each token** in the input sequence.

This representation goes into the model, which outputs scores that rank the likelihood of each token in its vocabulary as being the next one in the sequence.

Based on these scores, we have multiple strategies to select the tokens to complete the sentence (usually token with the **maximum score**).  
But there are more advanced decoding strategies. Eg: **Beam Search** explores multiple candidate sequences to find the one with the **maximum total score** \- even if some individual tokens have lower scores.

**Attention Is All You Need:**  
The process of identifying the most relevant words to predict the next token has proven to be incredibly effective and are done by Attention techniques.

**Context Length**: maximum number of tokens the LLM can process and the maximum attention span it has

**Prompt**: The input sequence you provide an LLM

**How are LLMs trained?**  
LLMs are trained on large datasets of text, where they learn to predict the next word in a sequence through a **self-supervised or masked language modeling** objective

From this unsupervised learning, the model learns the **structure** of the language and **underlying patterns** in text, allowing the model to **generalize to unseen data**.

After this initial pre-training, LLMs can be **fine-tuned** on a **supervised learning** objective to perform **specific tasks**.

**How can I use LLMs?**

1) Run Locally (if you have sufficient hardware)  
2) Use a Cloud/API (via the Hugging Face Serverless Inference API)

**How are LLMs used in AI Agents?**  
Providing the foundation for **understanding & generating human language**  
They can interpret user instructions, maintain context in conversations, define a plan & decide which tools to use  
LLM is the brain of the Agent
